!!【柯林斯英汉双解大词典】

:<div>

cry /kraɪ/

(crying,cried,cries) 

1. V-I When you cry , tears come from your eyes, usually because you are unhappy or hurt. 哭 

例： I hung up the phone and started to cry. 我挂掉电话，开始哭了起来。 

例： He cried with anger and frustration. 他愤怒而失望地哭了。 

2. N-SING Cry is also a noun. 哭 

例： A nurse patted me on the shoulder and said, 'You have a good cry, dear.' 一个护士拍着我的肩膀，说道：“亲爱的，你就痛痛快快地哭吧。” 

3. crying N-UNCOUNT 啼哭 

例： She had been unable to sleep for three days because of her 13-week-old son's crying. 由于她13周大的儿子的啼哭，她3天没睡着觉了。 

4. V-T If you cry something, you shout it or say it loudly. 大声叫喊 

例： 'Nancy Drew,' she cried, 'you're under arrest!' “南茜·德鲁，”她喊道：“你被捕了！” 

5. PHRASAL VERB Cry out means the same as . 大叫 

例： 'You're wrong, quite wrong!' Henry cried out, suddenly excited. “你错了，大错特错！”亨利突然激动起来，大声叫道。 

6. N-COUNT A cry is a loud, high sound that you make when you feel a strong emotion such as fear, pain, or pleasure. 尖叫 

例： A cry of horror broke from me. 我发出的一声惊恐的尖叫。 

7. N-COUNT A cry is a shouted word or phrase, usually one that is intended to attract someone's attention. 喊叫声 

例： Thousands of Ukrainians burst into cries of 'bravo.' 数千名乌克兰人放声高呼“好！” 

8. N-COUNT You can refer to a public protest about something or an appeal for something as a cry of some kind. (抗议某事、为某事请愿的) 公众呼声 [journalism] 

例： There have been cries of outrage about this expenditure. 公众对这项开支发出了愤怒的呼声。 

9. N-COUNT A bird's or an animal's cry is the loud, high sound that it makes. (鸟的) 啼叫声; (动物的) 嚎叫声 

例： ...the cry of a seagull. …一只海鸥的鸣叫声。 

10.  →  see also crying 

11. to cry your eyes out→see eye 

12. a shoulder to cry on→see shoulder

